INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '58a3ce02-5f8c-40f3-8d35-b8a5636f9019',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Jest + Testing Library — Query by Role, Not by Class$escape$,
  $escape$Most Jest test suites break silently when developers rename a CSS class or restructure markup. That's because they're testing implementation, not behaviour. Testing Library's philosophy flips this: query what the user perceives, not what the DOM looks like internally.

Prefer `getByRole('button', { name: /submit/i })` over `querySelector('.btn-primary')` or `getByTestId('submit-btn')`. Roles map to ARIA semantics — a `<button>` is always 'button', an `<input type="checkbox">` is always 'checkbox'. Your test survives refactors as long as the user-facing contract holds.

Query priority (highest to lowest): `getByRole` → `getByLabelText` → `getByPlaceholderText` → `getByText` → `getByDisplayValue` → `getByAltText` → `getByTitle` → `getByTestId`. Reach for `getByTestId` only when semantic alternatives are genuinely unavailable.

Pair this with `userEvent` over `fireEvent` — `userEvent.click()` dispatches the full browser event sequence (pointerdown, mousedown, focus, click), catching bugs that raw `fireEvent.click()` masks. With Jest's jsdom environment, this distinction matters because jsdom simulates, not renders.$escape$,
  $escape$import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react';
import userEvent from '@testing-library/user-event';
import SubmitForm from './SubmitForm';

test('submits form when button is clicked', async () => {
  const user = userEvent.setup();
  const onSubmit = jest.fn();

  render(<SubmitForm onSubmit={onSubmit} />);

  await user.type(screen.getByLabelText(/email/i), 'dev@byteai.com');
  await user.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /submit/i }));

  expect(onSubmit).toHaveBeenCalledWith({ email: 'dev@byteai.com' });
});$escape$,
