INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '8e5e3ecb-8df8-436e-9837-57367f52f275',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Jest Integration Testing — Mock at the Boundary, Not the Internals$escape$,
  $escape$Integration tests in Jest verify that multiple components wire together correctly. The key discipline: mock external boundaries (APIs, localStorage, third-party modules), never internal collaborators. If you mock a child component inside a parent integration test, you're just writing a unit test with extra steps.

Use `jest.mock()` at the module level to stub network calls via `msw` or by mocking `fetch` directly. Prefer `@testing-library/react` with `render` to mount the full component tree, then assert on DOM output — not implementation details. `waitFor` and `findBy*` queries handle async state updates cleanly.

A common mistake: mocking `useCartStore` or a context provider when testing a checkout flow. Instead, wrap the tree in the real provider with seeded state. Mock only the `POST /orders` fetch at the network layer. This catches wiring bugs — wrong prop drilling, missing context, broken event chains — that pure unit tests miss entirely. Keep `beforeEach` resets with `jest.clearAllMocks()` to prevent cross-test bleed.$escape$,
  $escape$// checkout.integration.test.tsx
import { render, screen, fireEvent, waitFor } from '@testing-library/react';
import { CartProvider } from '../context/CartContext';
import CheckoutFlow from '../components/CheckoutFlow';

global.fetch = jest.fn();

beforeEach(() => {
  jest.clearAllMocks();
  (fetch as jest.Mock).mockResolvedValue({
    ok: true,
    json: async () => ({ orderId: 'abc-123' }),
  });
});

it('submits cart and shows confirmation', async () => {
  render(
    <CartProvider initialItems={[{ id: 1, name: 'Pro Plan', qty: 1 }]}>
      <CheckoutFlow />
    </CartProvider>
  );

  fireEvent.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /confirm order/i }));

  await waitFor(() =>
    expect(screen.getByText('Order abc-123 confirmed')).toBeInTheDocument()
  );
  expect(fetch).toHaveBeenCalledWith('/api/orders', expect.objectContaining({ method: 'POST' }));
});$escape$,
