INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '0970bcb7-de85-48ad-9c51-36d54acc2248',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Jest Snapshot Testing — When It Helps vs When It Becomes Noise$escape$,
  $escape$Jest snapshots shine for stable, pure output: serialized data structures, utility function return values, or small UI components where unintended changes matter. Call `expect(tree).toMatchSnapshot()` once, commit the `.snap` file, and Jest catches regressions automatically.

The noise creeps in when snapshots wrap large component trees. Every prop rename, className tweak, or third-party library bump fails the snapshot — forcing mindless `jest --updateSnapshot` runs that defeat the purpose. Developers stop reading diffs and just update blindly.

Prefer `toMatchInlineSnapshot()` for small, stable outputs — the snapshot lives in the test file, so reviewers see it in the PR diff and can reason about it. For component testing, snapshot only the critical subtree using `react-test-renderer` with `toJSON()`, not the entire DOM.

Delete snapshots for components under active churn. Use `--ci` flag in pipelines to block any automatic snapshot creation, forcing explicit intent. Reserve full-tree snapshots for generated code, serialized configs, or CLI output — places where byte-level accuracy is the actual contract.$escape$,
  $escape$import renderer from 'react-test-renderer';
import { Badge } from './Badge';

// Good: small, stable subtree
test('Badge renders correct variant class', () => {
  const tree = renderer.create(<Badge variant="success">Done</Badge>).toJSON();
  expect(tree).toMatchInlineSnapshot(`
    <span className="badge badge--success">
      Done
    </span>
  `);
});

// Bad: avoid snapshotting entire page layouts —
// one Tailwind class change nukes the snapshot.$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
